Customer-Facing Menu Redesign Plan

Goal
Redesign the public customer experience into a professional, mobile-first restaurant QR menu. Customers should immediately see food, categories, search, prices, and offers with minimal friction.

Keep the existing Next.js app, admin system, Firebase data structure, and upload flow unless a change is required for the customer experience. Focus primarily on:
- app/page.tsx
- app/menu/MenuClient.tsx
- app/menu/page.tsx
- app/layout.tsx
- app/globals.css
- components/MobileContainer.tsx

Implementation Priority
- Core first: typography, design tokens, /menu layout, visible search, sticky category tabs, readable cards, consistent pricing, and mobile QA.
- Enhancement second: debounced or deferred search, touch micro-interactions, PWA metadata, and image optimization.
- Premium polish after layout is stable: scrollspy category highlighting and JSON-LD structured data.

Phase 1: Product Direction And Visual Standard [DONE]

Objective
Set a clear professional direction before editing components.

Instructions
- Treat /menu as the primary customer QR-code destination.
- Build for mobile first, then make sure desktop still looks clean.
- Prioritize speed, readability, and food discovery over cinematic presentation.
- Keep a premium restaurant feel, but reduce heavy glass effects and visual clutter.
- Add a modern, clean sans-serif font through next/font in app/layout.tsx.
- Preferred English fonts: Plus Jakarta Sans, Inter, or Outfit.
- If Arabic support is expected soon, plan for Cairo, Tajawal, or Noto Sans Arabic.
- Do not rely on browser default typography.
- Define customer-facing design tokens in app/globals.css or tailwind.config.js.
- Include tokens for background, surface, elevated surface, border, muted text, main text, accent gold, active state, card radius, control radius, shadow, and standard spacing.
- Use CSS variables where practical so the brand style can be tuned from one place.
- Use real food imagery as the main visual appeal instead of decorative gradients.
- Use one warm accent color, preferably amber or gold, only for prices, active states, highlights, and key actions.
- Avoid tiny text, excessive blur, nested cards, oversized decorative effects, and complicated card layouts.
- Use clear, consistent spacing and strong contrast.
- Keep tap targets at least 44px high.
- Use readable text sizes: body copy around 13px to 15px minimum.
- Use consistent border radius, preferably 8px to 12px for cards and controls.
- Use consistent currency formatting everywhere, preferably EGP 120 or 120 EGP.
- Remove all corrupted symbols, placeholder copy, and temporary customer-facing text.

Deliverables
- A small customer-facing design system using existing Tailwind/CSS patterns.
- Clear rules for backgrounds, cards, category tabs, buttons, prices, empty states, and text hierarchy.
- Font setup in app/layout.tsx using next/font.
- Design tokens in globals.css or Tailwind config.

Acceptance Criteria
- The design feels like a real restaurant menu, not a prototype.
- The first screen is useful immediately on a phone.
- Text is readable on small mobile screens.
- Important actions are obvious without explanation.
- Typography is consistent across the public customer pages.
- Colors, radius, spacing, and shadows come from shared tokens instead of one-off values.

Phase 2: Make /menu The Main Customer Experience [DONE]

Objective
Redesign app/menu/MenuClient.tsx so customers can browse the menu immediately.

Required Layout
- Sticky top header with logo or restaurant name.
- Search input directly under the header.
- Horizontal sticky category tabs visible by default.
- All tab at the beginning of the category list.
- Offers or featured items near the top if available.
- Menu items grouped by category.
- Clear empty states for no items and no search results.

Instructions
- Remove the collapsed category dropdown as the main navigation.
- Replace it with horizontally scrollable category tabs.
- Keep the active category visually obvious.
- Use the existing searchTerm state, but add a real search input.
- Search should match item names and preferably descriptions.
- When searching, show matching items clearly across categories.
- Add a clear search button only if useful; otherwise update results as the user types.
- Use debounced search or React useDeferredValue so typing stays smooth.
- Recommended debounce delay: around 250ms to 300ms if using a manual debounce.
- Do not add network requests for search unless the menu becomes too large for local filtering.
- Add a "Clear search" action when no results are found.
- Fix corrupted characters currently used for the dropdown arrow and empty-state emoji.
- Avoid hover-only interactions because customers mostly use touch devices.
- Keep sticky elements compact so they do not consume too much vertical space.
- Premium enhancement: add scrollspy category highlighting after the menu section layout is stable.
- Use IntersectionObserver to update the active category tab while the user scrolls.
- When a user taps a category, scroll smoothly to that section and keep the active state in sync.
- Disable or simplify scrollspy behavior while search is active, because search results may not follow full category sections.

Acceptance Criteria
- A customer can open /menu, search, switch categories, and read prices within 5 seconds.
- Category navigation remains accessible while scrolling.
- Search is visible and usable.
- No content is clipped on small phones.
- Empty states are clean and professional.
- Typing in search does not cause visible lag.
- If scrollspy is implemented, the active tab matches the section currently in view.

Phase 3: Redesign Menu Item Cards [DONE]

Objective
Make each item card easy to scan while still supporting images, sizes, serving details, and add-ons.

Recommended Card Structure
- Left side: stable square food image.
- Right side: item name, short description, and main price.
- Bottom area: optional badges for weight, pieces, or skewers.
- For items with sizes, show "From EGP X" on the main card.
- Show size prices in a clean compact list or expandable area.
- Show add-ons as secondary information under "Extras" without crowding the card.

Instructions
- Replace the dense 3-column size grid if it becomes too hard to read.
- Use a tasteful image placeholder when an item has no image.
- Do not display "No Image" as customer-facing text.
- Avoid image hover zoom on mobile-first cards.
- Add touch-friendly active states to tappable cards, category tabs, and buttons.
- Recommended effect: active:scale-[0.98] or active:scale-95 with a fast transition.
- Keep micro-animations subtle and functional; they should make the interface feel responsive under the finger.
- Keep price highly visible and consistently formatted.
- Keep long item names from breaking the layout.
- Avoid generic repeated fallback descriptions such as "Authentic Egyptian delicacy prepared with premium ingredients."
- If no real description exists, either hide the description line or show a short category-relevant fallback only if approved.
- Keep cards visually calm: subtle background, light border, readable text, limited effects.

Acceptance Criteria
- Item names and prices are readable at a glance.
- Cards remain stable with long names, no images, many sizes, and add-ons.
- Price and currency are consistent.
- No card feels crowded on mobile.
- Taps on cards, tabs, and buttons have immediate visual feedback.
- Animations do not delay browsing or make scrolling feel heavy.

Phase 4: Improve Entry Page / [DONE]

Objective
Make the homepage support the QR menu flow instead of slowing it down.

Preferred Direction
- QR codes should point directly to /menu.
- If / remains public, make it a lightweight brand entry with immediate menu access.

Instructions
- Do not use a fixed h-screen layout when offers are present; use min-h-screen and allow scrolling.
- Replace dollar pricing with the real currency.
- Keep copy short, brand-specific, and useful.
- Make offers visually connected to the menu.
- Keep the primary "View Menu" action immediately visible.
- Consider redirecting / to /menu if the restaurant wants the fastest QR experience.
- If a cinematic welcome screen remains, make sure it does not block customers from quickly seeing the menu.

Acceptance Criteria
- The homepage does not cut off content on small phones.
- Customers can reach the menu immediately.
- The homepage feels like a restaurant entry point, not a marketing page.

Phase 5: Brand, Metadata, And Content Polish [DONE]

Objective
Make the public site feel finished and trustworthy.

Instructions
- Update app/layout.tsx metadata with the real restaurant name and description.
- Replace "Restaurant Menu" with the real brand name.
- Add favicon and app icons if assets are available.
- Add theme-color metadata so the mobile browser top bar matches the restaurant theme.
- Add a public manifest.json for basic PWA/app-like behavior.
- Include app name, short name, icons, start_url, display mode, background color, and theme color in the manifest.
- Set the page language intentionally. Use English for now unless Arabic support is required.
- Prepare layout decisions for future Arabic support if needed.
- Use consistent naming: Elfatatry, menu, offers, categories, and item labels.
- Ensure all prices use the same currency format.
- Remove temporary comments and placeholder code from customer-facing files.
- Replace generic product copy with real restaurant copy.
- Avoid self-referential UI text that describes the page instead of helping the customer.
- Premium enhancement: add JSON-LD structured data when real restaurant details are available.
- Use Schema.org Restaurant data for name, logo, menu URL, cuisine, phone, address, opening hours, and price range.
- Add Menu/MenuSection data only if it can be generated accurately from the available menu data.
- Do not invent business details for structured data.

Acceptance Criteria
- Browser title and shared links look professional.
- Customer-facing text is brand-specific and polished.
- No corrupted characters, temporary copy, or placeholder descriptions remain.
- Mobile browser theme color matches the visual direction.
- PWA manifest is valid if added.
- JSON-LD contains only accurate restaurant information if added.

Phase 6: Performance And Image Standards [DONE]

Objective
Make the menu fast and reliable on restaurant Wi-Fi and mobile data.

Instructions
- Compress public/images/general/BG.png and public/images/general/Home.png.
- Convert large static images to WebP or AVIF where practical.
- Keep original source assets only if needed; serve optimized assets in the UI.
- Use Next Image with appropriate sizes values.
- Do not load heavy background images before critical menu content if they are not necessary.
- Make sure uploaded Cloudflare R2 images always resolve to a public URL.
- Ensure NEXT_PUBLIC_R2_DOMAIN or equivalent public asset domain is configured.
- Add simple skeleton or loading states for menu content.
- Avoid heavy animation delays in long menu lists.
- Keep animation durations short, especially for cards in long lists.
- Avoid staggered entrance delays for every item in large categories.
- Ensure debounced or deferred search still feels instant to the customer.
- Keep scrolling smooth on mobile.

Acceptance Criteria
- First screen appears quickly.
- Menu remains readable while images load.
- No uploaded item images are broken.
- Static assets are not unnecessarily large.
- Scrolling is smooth on mobile.
- Search and category switching stay responsive with a large menu.
- PWA metadata and theme-color do not introduce broken icon or manifest requests.

Phase 7: Customer QA Checklist [DONE]

Objective
Verify the redesigned menu behaves correctly in real customer scenarios.

Test Viewports
- iPhone SE size.
- Modern iPhone size.
- Medium Android size.
- Desktop narrow browser.
- Desktop wide browser.

Test Data Scenarios
- No categories.
- No items.
- Many categories.
- Category with many items.
- Item with no image.
- Item with long name.
- Item with no description.
- Item with one price.
- Item with multiple sizes.
- Item with serving details.
- Item with add-ons.
- Search with results.
- Search with no results.
- Fast typing into search.
- Clearing search after no results.
- Tapping category tabs repeatedly.
- Scrolling through categories with scrollspy enabled, if implemented.
- Offers enabled.
- Offers disabled.
- Missing favicon or app icon assets.
- Manifest present and valid, if implemented.
- JSON-LD present and valid, if implemented.

Technical Checks
- Run: node_modules\.bin\tsc.cmd --noEmit --pretty false
- Run: node_modules\.bin\eslint.cmd app components lib --ext .ts,.tsx --no-cache
- Run: npm.cmd run build

Notes
- npm run lint may fail on this Windows machine because PowerShell script execution or the Next eslint cache can be blocked.
- If npm run lint fails for that reason, use npm.cmd or the direct eslint command above.
- Investigate any npm.cmd run build timeout before deployment.

Final Target
The finished customer-facing site should feel instant, readable, attractive, food-focused, and trustworthy. The main goal is not only to make the app prettier; it is to remove friction so every customer can scan the QR code, find food, read prices, and choose quickly from a phone.
